 &lt;p class="feedback-card__text"&gt;Was this page helpful to you?&lt;/p&gt;</description></item><item><title>Bit Flipping</title><link>https://dangpham112000.github.io/docs/research/security/bit_flipping/</link><pubDate>Thu, 16 Jan 2025 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://dangpham112000.github.io/docs/research/security/bit_flipping/</guid><description>&lt;h1 id="bit-flipping-attack"&gt;
 Bit Flipping Attack
 &lt;a class="anchor" href="#bit-flipping-attack"&gt;#&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;/h1&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;As you can see in the &lt;a href="https://dangpham112000.github.io/docs/research/security/packet_sniffing/"&gt;Packet Sniffing&lt;/a&gt; section, we have a discussion about how messages that go through the internet can easily be seen by hackers. One of our protection solutions is to &lt;strong&gt;encrypt all packets that go through the internet&lt;/strong&gt;, but &lt;strong&gt;is it enough?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;h2 id="use-case"&gt;
 Use case
 &lt;a class="anchor" href="#use-case"&gt;#&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Attacking financial systems&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;h2 id="how-it-works"&gt;
 How it works
 &lt;a class="anchor" href="#how-it-works"&gt;#&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;An attacker alters bits in the ciphertext to produce a predictable change in the plaintext&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;By flipping specific bits, the attacker can control certain parts of the plaintext, potentially altering critical information&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;This manipulation allows the attacker to modify the encrypted message without needing to decrypt it first&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src="https://dangpham112000.github.io/research/security/bit_flipping/bit_flipping.png" alt="bit_flipping" /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</description></item></channel></rss>